North Korea says no to unilateral disarmament if there is no confidence
North Korea's foreign minister on Saturday informed the United Nations that continued sanctions have increased its distrust of the United States and that the country would not surrender its nuclear weapons under those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important steps to show its goodwill” last year, including stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test fields and committing to nuclear weapons and technology proliferation.
"However, we do not see the corresponding response from the US," he added.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, there will be no unilateral disarmament on our part first.”
As Ri resumed well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as had happened with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean peninsula while Trump ensured North Korea's security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted easing harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its coercive goal, and even opposes 'declaring the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream for those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions exacerbate our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the other side of this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached a dead end."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after “evil president” Trump called Kim “a rocket man on a suicide mission.”
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in taking action for disarmament, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes.
Trump said Wednesday that there was no deadline for that, and that “it doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three or five months.”
China and Russia are discussing whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council: “Compliance with the Security Council’s sanctions must continue firmly and without exception until we observe total, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then commented that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying he had made progress, just hours after North Korea denounced him for making "mafia claims."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea vowed to dismantle a missile site, as well as a nuclear complex, if the United States took “corresponding measures.”
He pointed out that Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he was requesting were the security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore and the progress towards normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
This year, a new course at Harvard University is making all its students sleep more in order to combat the growth of the male culture of studying all night long stimulated by caffeine.
One academic found that students at the world’s number one university often lack the basics about how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
She was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact lack of sleep had on learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why are you only telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said no one had told her about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, which was launched this year for the first time, explains to students the basics about how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to present the course after discovering that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deficit affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed of how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this information, just as we have a right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke tobacco," Czeisler added.
The pride culture of staying up all night, he says, still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the growing pressure for students to fall asleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring you get enough sleep and good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, she points out. Even avoiding getting fat, since lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which makes you constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push a course across campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to request all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm to go to bed, as well as to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can unbalance the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
