Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report from the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Conservation Commission, there is a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the commission, increasingly uneven outcrop conditions are being observed in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which may mean that concentrations are decreasing.
The red tide stretches approximately 210 km off the coast from the northern Pinellas counties to the southern Lee counties.
Concentrations can be found 16 km away from the coast of Hillsboro County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
The presence of mid-level concentrations on or off the coast of Pinellas County last week, background and elevated concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, background and mid-level concentrations on Charlotte County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of Collier County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of Collier County has been reported.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No such cases have been reported in Northwest Florida for the past week.
